                <h1>TravelRoute <a href="https://github.com/StriveX/TravelRoute"><small>https://github.com/StriveX/TravelRoute</small></a></h1>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-7">
                <p>Sometimes we read about or hear about interesting places across the world. We want to go some day but forget this place few days later. This app help people bookmark the locations with fascinating stories or pictures. People could view their dreaming places on map and plan trip accordingly. For example, you heard of Golden Gate Bridge, Ferry Building, Coit Tower, and marked these places on map. On some weekend during your intership, you select marked places around San Francisco, then the app will find a shortest path leading you to every place.</p>

                <p>This is the typical Traveling Salesman Problem(TSP), which is known as NP hard. There are several algorithms for this problem. First is the Brute Force solution that loop through each possible path and find the minimum. There is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2-opt">2-Opt</a> solution that switch a pair of edges each time and keep track of the minimum. In practical, when a user select lots of places, the execution could take a long time. In this problem, we want to find the "good enough" solution with heuristic method: "randomly" chooses a pair of edges to switch. But this easily stuck at a local minimum and never reaches the optimal solution.</p>

                <p>Simulated Annealing method is a statistical way for solving most optimization problem. In simulated annealing we keep a temperature variable to simulate this heating process. We initially set it high and then allow it to slowly 'cool' as the algorithm runs. While this temperature variable is high the algorithm will be allowed, with more frequency, to accept solutions that are worse than our current solution. This gives the algorithm the ability to jump out of any local optimums it finds itself in early on in execution. As the temperature is reduced so is the chance of accepting worse solutions, therefore allowing the algorithm to gradually focus in on a area of the search space in which hopefully, a close to optimum solution can be found. <sup><a href="http://www.theprojectspot.com/tutorial-post/simulated-annealing-algorithm-for-beginners/6">[1]</a></sup></p>

                <p>Here is another divide and conquer solution I developed: group points bottom-up, and conduct general TSP algorithm top-down: first, bring close points together as one group (cluster) by defining a distance benchmark. When a new point is added into a group, the group center is updated. Repeat this process by regarding each group as a point until the number of points is under some small number. Now running TSP algorithm starting from the highest level and then to lower level. Since TSP has O(n!) complexity, this will exponentially reduce the running time.</p>
